And the wall collapsed...
Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: twenty years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best and which had the greatest impact on the planet?
a) The bloody suppression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few respond to c).
For the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe—and therefore to the reconstruction of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the head of Poland, General Jaruzelski, assessed that the country's economic problems were too severe for him to face alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he asked - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of negotiations, he reached an historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc would be able to take part.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) never for a moment considered that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they never imagined they would be expelled from power.
Yet, that is exactly what happened.
Looking back, it is surprising that there could have been doubts.
Solidarnosc campaigned boldly.
An adapted poster of a classic Western film, *The Man Who Would Be King*, became a huge success: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot in place of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
On June 4th, was the day of judgment.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was about to give birth to summer, the voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to a final perversion that turned into an involuntary self-embarrassment.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting candidates of their choice, had to cross out the names of those they did not want—effectively all the communists listed on the voting ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the long-awaited popular uprising that Poland had been expecting, the revenge on December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarnosc, and sent its leaders to prison.
The revolution by the pen!
Handled with style, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters tore up their ballots entirely, effectively beheading the old regime with a single decisive act.
Other voters savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"that one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "look, this apparatchik got rich off our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
By contrast, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates took the trouble to put up posters.
Most relied on the monopoly they held over the media to spread their message: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist."
One can say to his credit that the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to declare: "Our defeat is total," and that a political solution must be found.
It meant that he wanted neither violence nor fraud, and the communists would have to live with the election result.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarnosc was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would set an example for the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anti-communists all around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what had seemed impossible just days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began dismantling the fences erected along the border with Austria—a hole in the Iron Curtain.
At Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European House" and rejected the interventionist doctrine of Brejnev.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible—until the day freedom broke out.
